[Student "S"]
{North is to play 4\H. East leads the \DJ.

With three unavoidable \S losers you cannot afford to lose a \C. So you either have to guess the location of the\CQ or (DRUMROLL) pull off an elimination play! Win the \DK, then pull trumps, it takes two rounds.

Next you eliminate the \Ds by playing \DA then ruffing the \D8.

Execute the throw-in by leading a \S.

The defense is in with a \S and they are welcome to take two more \Ss. But then they will to have to play a \S or a \D, giving you a ruff-sluff, or else lead a \C which finds the \CQ for you.

Using elimination plays makes you a better player. But in Bridge, no matter how skillful you are, there will always be a luck factor.

Here you were lucky the defense didn't start by taking their three \Ss. If they had, you would not have been able to pull off the throw-in, and would have had to try your luck with  guessing who had the \CQ. }
[Play "W"]DJ

